1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,199
Before we wrap up the core content, here are some inclusive practice tips you can start using today.

2
00:00:07,199 --> 00:00:11,199
These are small, concrete actions that make a real difference.

3
00:00:11,199 --> 00:00:14,399
Tip number one: Always ask — never assume.

4
00:00:14,399 --> 00:00:19,199
If you are not sure how to support someone, ask them directly.

5
00:00:19,199 --> 00:00:26,399
A simple question like "How can I best assist you today?" respects their expertise about their own needs.

6
00:00:26,399 --> 00:00:30,000
Tip number two: Make your space scan a habit.

7
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:34,399
Before your next shift, look at your workspace with fresh eyes.

8
00:00:34,399 --> 00:00:37,600
Can someone in a wheelchair reach the counter?

9
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:40,800
Is the signage readable from five feet away?

10
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:44,000
Is there a clear path to the door?

11
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Tip number three: Speak to the person, not their companion.

12
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,800
When a patient is accompanied by a support person or interpreter, direct your conversation to the patient.

13
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:56,800
Make eye contact with them.

14
00:00:56,800 --> 00:01:00,000
They are the expert on their own care.

15
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Tip number four: Offer information in more than one format.

16
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:12,799
If you are handing out a printed form, ask if the person would prefer large print, an electronic version, or verbal instructions.

17
00:01:12,799 --> 00:01:19,599
These four tips connect directly to the Accessibility in Practice model — awareness, communication, environment, and response.
